Ozone has far-reaching impacts on air quality and climate, perhaps best described by the US
EPA as "good up high, bad nearby." When nearby, ozone exposure can harm human and
ecosystem health. When up high, ozone has a buffer effect against incoming UV light from the sun.

text.tspan: Studies on human exposure show that ozone pollution poses higher risks of both short-term
and long-term health impacts. There are a number of air quality guidelines for ozone, including
the US EPA's air quality index, whose ozone scale is featured here.

Scientists have found that climate change exerts impacts on ozone levels, where a warming climate
leads to the formation of greater ozone levels in polluted areas. Given this phenomenon, emission
controls may need to be made stricter in major cities in order to meet air quality standards for ozone.
Warmer temperatures are accompanied by more water vapor in the
air. The radicals from water vapor dismantle ozone through chemical
reactions. Thanks to this phenomenon, natural levels of surface ozone
are projected to decrease. Sparsely, less polluted areas will therefore
either see no net impact or potentially lower ozone levels.
Ozone is produced more frequently at higher temperatures in drier
environments. This leaves polluted urban areas in the summertime
particularly susceptible to increases in surface ozone levels.

g.text: Ozone smog forms when sunlight meets nitrogen oxides (NOx), volatile organic compounds (VOCs), and carbon
monoxide (CO). Sources of NOx include power plants and motor vehicles. Sources for VOCs include motor vehicles,
chemical plants, refineries, and factories. Forests also emit VOCs. CO is mostly emitted from motor vehicles.

text.tspan: Monitoring suggests that ozone pollution can stunt tree growth and cause
foliar injury, change species composition, and make trees and crops more vulnerable
to insects and disease. Further up in the atmosphere, ozone acts as a greenhouse gas.
